==== Greedy stays ahead

+ *Label your algorithm's partial solutions, and a general solution* e.g \
  Let $A = {a_1, a_2, ..., a_k}$ be the solution generated by your algorithm, with elements appearing in the order they are added. Let $O = {o_1, o_2, ..., o_k}$ be an arbitrary (or optimal) feasible solution. Ordering of $O$ is generally similar to the ordering of $A$.

+ *Find a measure* \
  Define a _measure_ $f(dot)$ by which greedy stays ahead of a general / optimal solution. e.g. $f(a_1, ..., a_j)$ might be the last completion time of the first $j$ jobs.

+ *Prove greedy stays ahead (the Inductive step)* \
  Show that the partial solutions constructed by greedy are always just as good as the initial segments of your other solution, based on the measure you selected.
  - For all indices $r <= k$, prove by induction that $f(a_1, ..., a_r)[>=, <=]f(o_1, ..., o_r)$.

